Spiny Lobster Abundance, Community Size Structure, and Fishing Pressure Along the Santa Barbara Coast (2012-2018)

ESM 206 Assignment 4

Cameryn Brock and Allie Hacker

11/17/2019

Introduction

California spiny lobsters (Panulirus interruptus) are an important species in Southern California’s coastal giant kelp forests (Figure 1). Additionally, California spiny lobsters are important in California’s commercial and recreational fishing industry. In California, they were responsible for more than $15,000,000 in revenue in the 2015/16 season, and their price per pound more than doubled between 2005 and 2015 (Frimodig and Buck 2017).

In 2012, two sites in this study, Isla Vista and Naples, were established as Marine Protected Areas (MPAs). MPAs are meant to conserve, manage, and protect natural or cultural resources (NOAA 2018). Effective MPAs have been shown to have more fish species and biomass than in normally fished areas (Edgar et al. 2014) and can benefit catch-rates for fisheries (Kerwath et al. 2013). In this study, we compare California spiny lobster samples from five sites on the Santa Barbara Coast from 2012-2018 to investigate how MPA status affects lobster abundance, community structure, and size.

California spiny lobster (Panulirus interruptus). Credit: Catalina Island Marine Institute

Data and Methods

California spiny lobster data were provided by the Environmental Data Initiative (Reed 2019). Lobster abundace (individuals) and size (mm) were determined by annual SCUBA surveys at five long term kelp forest research sites in the Santa Barbara Channel. Two of the sites, Isla Vista and Naples, were established as Marine Protected Areas (MPAs) in 2012. Data collection began in late summer of 2012 before the start of fishing season and is ongoing.

Changes in lobster abundance and shifts in lobster size distribution from 2012 to 2018 were explored for each study site. Mean lobster size (mm) at MPA sites and non-MPA sites was compared for both 2012 and 2018 using two-sample t-tests (alpha = 0.05). Mean lobster size in 2012 and 2018 was compared for MPA and non-MPA sites using two-sample t-tests. R software (version 3.5.1) and RStudio (version 1.2.1335) were used for data analysis and figure generation.

Results

1. Changes in annual lobster abundance.

California spiny lobster abundance increased from 2012 to 2018 at all five sampling locations (Figure 2). The two MPA sites (Isla Vista and Naples) had the lowest lobster abundance in 2012 and the greatest percent increase in lobster abundance from 2012 to 2018. The number of lobsters observed at Isla Vista increased 36-fold, from 26 in 2012 to 946 in 2018. At Naples, lobster abundance increased 49-fold, from 6 lobsters in 2012 to 298 in 2018.

Figure 2. California spiny lobster abundance in the Santa Barbara Channel from 2012 to 2018. Sites shown in turquoise were established as Marine Protected Areas (MPAs) in 2012.

2. Shifts in lobster size distributions.

Size distributions (Figure 3) were compared for all sites in 2012 and 2018. Most notably, the median for lobster size increased in MPA sites between 2012 and 2018. However, in non-MPA sites, the median size remained relatively the same during that time period.

Figure 3. California spiny lobster size distributions in the Santa Barbara Channel in 2012 and 2018. Sites shown in turquoise were established as Marine Protected Areas (MPAs) in 2012. White lines indicate the median lobster size for each facet.

3. Mean lobster size in MPA and non-MPA sites.

In addition to the lobster community size structure, mean lobster size was compared for MPA and non-MPA sites in 2012 and 2018 (Table 1).

Table 1. California spiny lobster mean size, standard deviation, and sample size for samples collected in MPA and non-MPA sites in 2012 and 2018. MPA sites include Isla Vista and Naples and non-MPA sites include Arroyo Quemado, Carpinteria, and Mohawk.

Standard Deviation (mm)
Sample Size
Year MPA Non-MPA MPA Non-MPA MPA Non-MPA
2012 67.4 74.9 12.2 12.4 32 199
2018 77.6 73.6 11.7 10.1 1244 561

Mean lobster size in MPA sites was larger in 2018 (77.6 ± 11.7mm, mean ± standard deviation) compared to 2012 (67.4 ± 12.2mm) and the increase was statistically significant with a large effect size (two-sample t-test, t (32) = -4.7, p < 0.0001, Cohen’s d = 0.87)). No significant change in mean lobster size was observed in sites that were not established as MPAs (Arroyo Quemado, Carpinteria, and Mohawk) between 2012 (74.9 ± 12.4mm) and 2018 (73.6 ± 10.1mm; two-sample t-test, t(296) = 1.3, p = 0.19, Cohen’s d = -0.12).

In 2012, mean lobster size in MPA sites was smaller than in non-MPA sites, and this difference was statistically significant with a moderate effect size (two-sample t-test, t(42) = -3.3, p = 0.0023 , Cohen’s d = -0.61). In 2018, mean lobster size was larger in MPAs than in non-MPAs, and that difference was statistically significant with a moderate effect size (two-sample t-test, t(1236) = 7.3, p < 0.0001, Cohen’s d = -0.35).

Summary

  • Lobster abundance increased at all sites from 2012 to 2018, with the largest increases at MPA sites (Figure 2).
  • Median lobster size increased at MPA sites from 2012 to 2018, but did not increase at non-MPA sites (Figure 3).
  • Mean lobster size was greater at non-MPA sites than at MPA sites in 2012, but in 2018, mean lobster size was greater at MPA sites than non-MPA sites (Table 1).
